    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "b1f969e67772202354c61560c61936500fb299b6"
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q102",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "process-states",
    "stem": "Which of the following is not a fundamental process state?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Ready",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Executed",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Terminated",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Blocked (can be substituted with wait)",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "The fundamental process states are new, ready, running, blocked (waiting) and terminated; 'Executed' is not one of them because the state is called running/executing, so B is the odd one out. Blocked (D) is a genuine state, so the bold key printed in the source PDF is the wrong one and B is correct.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2016,
      "originalNumber": 2
    },
    "keyProvenance": "derived",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "derived",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "2229c415e088cd20655722464283f8149f64f69c"
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q103",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "page-replacement",
    "stem": "LRU page replacement policy stands for",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Last replaced unit",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Least recently used",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Last restored unit",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Least required unit",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "LRU stands for Least Recently Used: it evicts the page whose most recent reference is furthest in the past, using locality of reference as a proxy for which page will be needed last. The other three expansions are invented terms.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2016,
      "originalNumber": 3
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "71f0a1622c0f876aa463aa653173e3c31924f575"
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q104",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "wireless-standards",
    "stem": "Another name for IEEE 802.11 a is",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Wi-Fi",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Ethernet",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "WiMAX",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "802.11 g",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "The whole IEEE 802.11 WLAN family, including 802.11a, is branded Wi-Fi. Ethernet is 802.3 and WiMAX is 802.16. The trap is D: 802.11a is a different PHY from 802.11g (5 GHz versus 2.4 GHz, though both reach 54 Mbps), so they are not other names for each other.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2016,
      "originalNumber": 4
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "137d7f06cab9e314cff82b4156f8c7773198a313"
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q105",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "kernel",
    "stem": "The kernel of the operating system remains in primary memory because",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "It manages interrupt calls",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "It is mostly used or called",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "The kernel is the most frequently executed code in the system: every system call, interrupt and context switch enters it, so paging it out would fault on nearly every dispatch, which is why it stays permanently resident. Managing interrupt calls (A) is a job the kernel performs, not the reason it must remain in primary memory.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2016,
      "originalNumber": 5
    },
    "keyProvenance": "derived",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "derived",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "f84e6c16ca6dffb3d8fab04bcdca7a245c1b5361"
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q107",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "digital-logic",
    "subtopic": "logic-gates",
    "stem": "The Nand gate output is low, if the 2 inputs are",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "00",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "01",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "10",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "11",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "NAND is NOT(AND), so the output is low only when the AND condition is satisfied, i.e. both inputs are 1: 1 NAND 1 = 0. Inputs 00, 01 and 10 all give an AND of 0, so the inverted output is 1 (high).",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2016,
      "originalNumber": 7
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "double",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "512eeec8e2fece610e5bb5715d665c4a3101503d"
  },
  {
    "id": "knpc2016-q108",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "data-structures-algorithms",
    "subtopic": "complexity",
    "stem": "Two main measures for the efficiency of an algorithm",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Processor and memory",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Complexity and capacity",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Time and space",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Data and space",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "explanation": "Algorithm efficiency is measured on two axes: time complexity (how many operations as a function of input size) and space complexity (how much extra memory). Processor and memory are the hardware resources, not the measures of the algorithm itself.",
    "source": {
      "file": "KOC 2012 EXAM (2).pdf",
      "exam": "KNPC",
      "tier": "gold",
      "year": 2016,
      "originalNumber": 8
    },
